							</script><div class="btn btn-xl btn-white btn-circle position-absolute shadow" style="top: 50%; transform: translateY(-50%)"><em class="material-icons" data-icon="play_arrow"></em></div></a></div><figcaption class="card-body"><div class="md-assembly-title font-weight-bold mb-5 d-inline-block font-16 font-sans-serif">Why do some trees lose their leaves in autumn?</div><div class="md-assembly-caption mt-5 text-muted font-14 font-serif  line-clamp"><span>Learn why leaves of deciduous trees change colour in autumn.</span><button class="js-more-btn d-none btn btn-unstyled font-12 bg-white js-content" aria-label="Toggle more/less fact data"><span class="link-blue">(more)</span></button></div><a class="font-14 mt-10 d-inline-block" href="/science/autumn-season/images-videos">See all videos for this article</a></figcaption></figure></div></div></div><button disabled="true" class="prev-button js-prev-button position-absolute btn btn-circle shadow btn-lg btn-blue m-20"><span class="material-icons" data-icon="keyboard_arrow_left"></span></button><button disabled="true" class="next-button js-next-button position-absolute btn btn-circle shadow btn-lg btn-blue m-20"><span class="material-icons" data-icon="keyboard_arrow_right"></span></button></div><!--[MOD2]--><span class="marker MOD2 mod-inline"></span><p class="topic-paragraph">The concept of autumn in European languages is connected with the harvesting of crops; in many <a class="md-dictionary-link md-dictionary-tt-off mw" data-term="cultures" href="https://www.merriam-webster.com/dictionary/cultures" data-type="MW">cultures</a> autumn, like the other seasons, has been marked by rites and festivals revolving around the seasonâ€™s importance in food production. Animals gather food in autumn in preparation for the coming winter, and those with fur often grow thicker coats. Many birds migrate toward the Equator to escape the falling temperatures. A common autumn phenomenon in the central and eastern United States and in <a href="https://www.britannica.com/place/Europe" class="md-crosslink autoxref" data-show-preview="true">Europe</a> is <span id="ref128251"></span><a href="https://www.britannica.com/science/Indian-summer" class="md-crosslink" data-show-preview="true">Indian summer</a>, a period of unseasonably warm <a href="https://www.britannica.com/science/weather" class="md-crosslink autoxref" data-show-preview="true">weather</a> that sometimes occurs in late October or November.</p></section>        <span class="md-signature"><a href="/editor/The-Editors-of-Encyclopaedia-Britannica/4419">The Editors of Encyclopaedia Britannica</a></span><span class="md-signature">This article was most recently revised and updated by <a href="/editor/Meg-Matthias/12593612">Meg Matthias</a>.</span><!--[END-OF-CONTENT]--><span class="marker end-of-content"></span><!--[AFTER-ARTICLE]--><span class="marker after-article"></span></div>

